Why America's President Bush cannot be re-elected
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and at the same time undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I have been cursed by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a campaign program that promised a foreign policy of "humility".
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush Doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policy at the ballot box, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The 9/11 terrorist attacks required a strong response.
However, they also led to the suspension of the critical process essential for democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of the impending problems.
Bush silenced criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For a duration of 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush directly played into Osama bin Laden's hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al-Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was bin Laden's unintended gift to Bush.
Immediately after September 11, there were spontaneous expressions of sympathy towards America all over the world.
These have given way to widespread resentment.
More people than on September 11 are now willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush likes to claim that the terrorists hate Americans for what they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqi civilians killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
The torture of inmates at Abu Ghraib prison was no less the work of a few "bad apples".
It was part of a system for handling prisoners established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands with him by addressing the fears triggered by the 9/11 attacks.
In times of danger, people rally around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by promoting a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people ultimately do not care about the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America if we fall for this.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in 9/11, although the 9/11 Commission - established by Bush and chaired by a Republican - has clearly stated that no such connection existed.
One wants to scream: „Wake up, America.
Don't you realize that we're being led around by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false assumptions from start to finish - if it ever comes to an end.
It was a war of choice, not necessity.
Moreover, America went to war under a pretext: no weapons of mass destruction were found, and there is no evidence of a connection to Al-Qaeda.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to liberate Iraq.
But democracy cannot be imposed by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad that they are rid of him.
America, however, had the duty to uphold law and order; instead, we watched idly as Baghdad and other cities were plundered.
If we really cared about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a larger number of soldiers for occupation.
We would have had to protect not only the oil ministry, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they used methods - such as entering private homes and mistreating prisoners - that offended and humiliated the population, and thereby sparked bitterness and anger.
The Bush administration's mistakes and miscalculations are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was disbanded, and then America tried to re-establish it.
First, the US attempted to eliminate the Baathists, then sought the help of America.
When the uprisings became unsustainable, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protege with a reputation as a "strong man" - an undemocratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to downplay the situation, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
Most of the western part of the country has been left to insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly fading.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has inflicted immeasurable damage on America, weakened its military strength, and undermined troop morale.
Before the war, America could project the impression of overwhelming strength.
No longer today.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush Administration on many other political issues, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war have so far reached nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush attacked John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to get us out of our predicament.
But it won't be easy for him either, because America is stuck in a quagmire.
Leading military experts and diplomats had warned Bush repeatedly not to invade Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process, arguing that any criticism of the commander-in-chief would put US troops at risk.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
Americans should take a moment to ask themselves: Who are we to blame for this mess?
A moment of reflection might raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy demeanor qualify him to remain America's commander-in-chief?
